  <h1 class="hidetitle">Security for the Layperson</h1>
  <h2>Usability is core to effective security controls</h2>
  <h3>Phil Vachon</h3>
  <p><i>Cybersecurity is not just a problem facing enterprises. Individual users face similar risks without expertise and support to back them up. Oftentimes, tools at users’ disposal to make life easier can make life even worse without the right expertise…</i></p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <p>My spouse and I were at our favorite coffee shop in our favorite vacation spot, sitting at our favorite table on our favorite patio. In this bucolic setting on the shores of Kalamalka Lake in British Columbia, a senior citizen who had long resided in the area saw us sitting with my Apple-branded laptop and stopped by our table to ask us younger folks some technology-related questions. Decades of being well trained as my family’s personal IT support service (that’s “service with a grimace”—each and every one of you reading this knows exactly what I am talking about) obliged me to answer, “But of course,” knowing full well that I was headed down a deep rabbit hole.</p>
  <p>The questioner, a local woman who was at least 75, was happy to have someone hear her out. So, she sat at our table and spun out her yarn. We’ve all heard some form of this tale before: She was a long-time Yahoo Mail user who had saved thousands of emails, including some important ones from family and friends. One day, she received an email warning her that she would lose access to her Yahoo Mail account and that all her emails would be deleted unless she paid her Yahoo service fee by calling the phone number listed in the email. Whatever might happen to all those emails she had diligently composed to <i>The Globe and Mail</i> and local politicians over the years if she didn’t take action? These were treasures she wanted to keep!</p>
  <p>The email call-to-action inspired such fear in her that she immediately called the number, beseeching the operator on the other end not to cut off her access to her Yahoo Mail account and, above all else, begging that her emails not be deleted. I’m sure many of you know what happened next…</p>
  <p>By preying on her fear of losing something so precious and personal, the operator demanded this poor woman’s Yahoo Mail account credentials to “fix” her account. The “operator” (more appropriately referred to as a scammer), proceeded to ransack her email account, looking most likely for personal information to beef up the next phase of the scam. The scammer convinced this poor woman to download a remote-control tool, first having her configure her Mac to allow any unsigned binary to run. Using that tool, they were able to get unlimited access to her bank accounts, along with any other accounts and private information she might access from her laptop. Classic social engineering applied with trapdoors in security-control design had enabled the scammer to take complete control of this woman’s life.</p>
  <p>In a last-ditch effort, she searched for an Apple technical support number and got help from a representative at Apple. The person answering the call at Apple recognized the remote access tool as a risk and helped her clean up her Mac. In the process, however, something happened to her Yahoo Mail account, leaving her unable to access her old emails… just as the phishing lure had threatened.</p>
  <p>As her story unfolded, my heart sank further with each new detail in the narrative. Once the attackers took control of her laptop, she’d realized something was amiss and called the laptop manufacturer. As a not-so-technically-savvy user, what other recourse did she have? Little did she realize, her problems spanned across several companies and products, few of which Apple could directly influence. (Ultimately, she asked whether or not I felt Best Buy’s Geek Squad could help her out. What would you have answered in this case?) On top of this, a senior citizen who had spent her life speaking to companies face to face or over the phone was left trying to storm the gates of several faceless corporations, many of which deliberately obfuscate these kinds of communication channels.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <h3>Don’t Blame the Victim</h3>
  <p>Social-engineering attacks continue unabated, with the power of stolen personal information amplifying their destructive results. On some level, this is a good sign for us in the security industry. We can pat ourselves on the back for having hardened the softer surface of much of the hardware, software, and infrastructure we rely on to securely deliver services today. Crooks have had to get much craftier as multifactor authentication, password managers, and other widely available tools have raised the bar (and subsequently, the cost) for those who would like to surreptitiously gain access to a victim’s accounts.</p>
  <p>With this increase in protection have come more aggressive phishing lures, info stealers who siphon up long-lived access credentials from victim’s devices, and human operators that socially engineer their marks from call centers around the world. The problem is that many of these attacks play on behaviors that evolved to protect and perpetuate the human race. Shamelessly threatening victims with loss of status, potential loneliness, or harm to family members are all tools commonly used by scammers.</p>
  <p>Human beings didn’t always live in the relative safety of modern cities. Hard-earned lessons in the deep past, perhaps hundreds of thousands of years ago, baked in instinctive behaviors and tools that help to rapidly identify threats. These instincts have helped us avoid predators, traps, or other serious risks. They call us to action whenever a threat is sensed through an <i>amygdala hijacking</i> of our higher functions, at the first indication of some immediate danger requiring quick and decisive action. Some studies suggest our IQ measurably drops when we’re in this state, and we become more prone to impulsive, reactive behavior without considering potential consequences as we might in our base state. By threatening a potential victim the right way, a scammer can trigger these altered states, turning us into even softer targets.</p>
  <p>The problem is greatly compounded when knowledge of these human behaviors is combined with the complexity of modern computing—the variety of passwords to keep track of, the unique workflows to follow when using those passwords (or resetting them), the differing tools needed to provide an added layer of security (SMS second factor? HOTP? TOTP? Microsoft Authenticator? Passkeys? A physical authenticator such as a Yubikey?)—together with the confusing nature of how authentication material gets stored and used once a user has been successfully authenticated. My experience is that many people in our industry can’t explain how these things work—never mind some poor phishing mark who is in a state of amygdala hijack.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <h3>Solving This in the Enterprise</h3>
  <p>In a corporate setting, we can avail ourselves of several tools. First, we guard authentication material (such as access tokens held on a device) jealously, ensuring that devices with appropriate access controls, patching policies, and monitoring tools are the only way to reach enterprise assets. This makes life worse for a malicious party installing a remote-access tool. If you can’t get malicious tools onto the device to impersonate the user, or if an info-stealer can’t be run successfully because endpoint detection and response (EDR) detects and blocks that, all the better.</p>
  <p>Second, we look to reduce the frequency with which users need to enter credentials—only once, always in the exact same place, and as infrequently as can be tolerated—requiring step-up authentication and reauthentication only when accessing sensitive resources. This policy means that, outside of what you define as your normal reauthentication flow, users should be alarmed if they’re being asked to enter credentials of any sort within your enterprise environment.</p>
  <p>Third, education helps. We must imbue our users with a healthy cynicism, helping them identify when someone is trying to trick them into lowering their guard. No matter how many systems we put in place to catch potential phishing attacks, some messages still trickle through. Coupling frequent training with low-friction tools to report and analyze potential targeted scams helps enable users to understand their role in identifying these scams and avoiding falling prey to them.</p>
  <p>Finally, most enterprises aspire to apply the principle of least privilege to user access. Any user, employee, client, or automated job should possess only the minimum degree of access required to perform their job function. In the vast majority of cases, a user doesn’t need to have system administrator privileges, the ability to become root, or even an interactive shell when accessing a production system. No user should have this level of ambient authority, especially on the endpoint with which they perform their day-to-day job.</p>
  <p>None of these provisions constitutes a silver bullet. Attackers can move faster than EDR, patch cycles could be lagging, or there might be some lingering legacy entitlements (or an undetected toxic combination of entitlements), creating significant ambient privilege risk. Thus, you must assume that whatever a user can do is their “ambient authority”—which is the same as the authority of any program or any other human being in front of a keyboard impersonating that user.</p>
  <p>It’s nice to be a corporation and to have these options. The average user with limited computer literacy, however, doesn’t have a team of experts on call who can help understand the risk to their posture, or explain how damaging it can be to cough up a credential—either or both of which can hinder the ability of anyone to solve this problem for the average person.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <h3>Trapdoors Around Built-in Controls</h3>
  <p>Dramatic improvements in modern operating-systems baseline, out-of-the-box security posture have made tremendous headway. Usage-model improvements, such as ensuring that a user does not run as administrator by default, have made great strides toward decreasing the effectiveness of some kinds of basic malware. Both Apple and Microsoft have introduced tools in their respective operating systems that validate the integrity of binaries shipped by a vendor and quickly revoke the permission to run those binaries in the event they turn out to be malicious.</p>
  <p>While Microsoft and Apple’s update cadence can feel binding, even intrusive, the ability to rapidly deploy software patches for vulnerabilities and reduce a user’s ability to bypass installing a patch has only improved security posture. From a pure information-security perspective, these are good improvements. Out of the gate, a layperson can feel stronger assurance that they can confidently use the device to conduct their day-to-day activities.</p>
  <p>For a number of reasons, these security features can also be disabled by the device’s owner. Part of this is its own form of trust in the sense that some security features can be hard to distinguish from monopoly-protecting features. A system with these security controls enabled, however, is indistinguishable from one that has them disabled, especially to a layperson. On top of that, it’s not difficult to guide even a nontechnical user through the deliberate steps to disable or bypass these controls. Many scammers have this in their playbook for when they encounter these roadblocks. So, this only slows things down for high-touch scams, such as a fake technical-support center.</p>
  <p>To make matters worse, even when working effectively, these security controls place mental load on users while they take day-to-day actions. Maybe it’s a legitimate application that requires frequent escalation to administrator privileges to perform some particular task. Perhaps it’s an unsigned binary downloaded from a trusted source. Time and again, user-experience studies show that every time we surface security risks to a user to make a decision, they will pick the path of least resistance to get them to the point where they can do whatever it is they originally set out to do. Few users will stop and consider the implications of an expired TLS (Transport Layer Security) certificate, and fewer still would be able to do the legwork to figure out if that was indicative of a real risk or a configuration error. In such a case, even a not-so-savvy scammer who is up to something untoward could instruct their mark to simply bypass any browser-provided warning.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <h3>Passkeys Only Make This Worse</h3>
  <p>With the introduction of new mechanisms for two-factor authentication, such as passkeys, life is getting more complicated for the less computer literate. While passkeys will end the era of easily phishable credentials, it complicates the hidden state and the need for a more complete mental model to understand sharp edge cases: What happens if my passkey doesn’t synchronize and I have to reauthenticate? Why don’t passkeys on my Mac work on Windows? What passkeys are valid for my mail account <i>at this moment?</i> When should I expect to use a passkey or my fallback credentials?</p>
  <p>The happy path for passkeys is brilliant. With a simple action and an authenticator, you’re in—with no more passwords to enter after an initial enrollment step. Once you step off this path, however, there’s space for confusion or a hidden enrollment by an adversary who steals your regular credentials. Adding this mental load to a senior citizen—or any user—will be detrimental. Inconsistent implementations make this harder to understand, because every website has a different way of enrolling and managing passkeys. Decoding unique behaviors in how different services use authentication material creates more opportunities for scammers to prey upon individuals.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <h3>Mental Models are not the Whole Answer</h3>
  <p>If a scammer can rely on the amygdala hijack or other emotional responses to lower peoples’ defenses, pressing users to develop a complete mental model of information security risk can’t be the only option. This isn’t to say education isn’t worthwhile. As technical people, our first instinct should be to share our knowledge and empathetically educate, and we should take every opportunity to do so. Unless this knowledge is internalized by a person, however, when emotions take over, their decision-making will probably not even detect the otherwise obvious risks. The ever-increasing complexity of authentication means that internalizing these risks becomes all that much harder.</p>
  <p>A senior citizen asking for help is a chance to educate in plain language. It can help to explain how providing someone with remote access to their computer gives that person the same power available to them if they were sitting in front of the keyboard. Giving them some insight into how phishing works can only help the next time a phishing email with a well-crafted lure arrives. But the once-bitten, twice-shy person with compromised mental faculties will probably not fall prey to this kind of scam again. It’s too bad they know how to talk about these types of risks only <i>after</i> they have already been compromised.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <h3>How do we stay ahead?</h3>
  <p>Usability is core to effective security controls. When you’re designing security controls for the masses, you must consider a much wider variety of end users, who have differing levels of knowledge, comprehension of risk, or even mental models of what the value of credentials might be.</p>
  <p>Our poor victim in this case was an easy mark. Technology, especially security technology, only made this worse. User agency is important, but secure design continues to fail the most important participant in any security system: the end user. By exposing the complexity of controls, making it too easy to disable controls without an adequate understanding of the impact, and turning authentication into a maze, we’ve only made it easier for scammers to trick our users. We need to do better. I’m just not quite sure how to accomplish that trick yet.</p>
